reviewText:
This game is basically a stripped down version of original XCOM with residual RPG elements.

Or more precisely, it's a rogue-like turn-based tactical space robot/alien/monster shooter with procedurally generated levels.

Gameplay is OK in general, but there are enough reasons to look the other way to spend your time on.

Here are some of them:
- Controls are awful, and prone to mistypes, which for rogue-likes is kind of a big deal;
- Map and layout of objects on it is awkward and takes some time to get used to;
- I'm pretty sure the only thing which can keep you playing (all 30 short levels) is the game's difficulty. Myself, after dying five times on the level 2 (talk about learning curve) of average difficulty, I switched to easy and then was really bored most of the way;
- Monster types are limited, they're stupid, and when they manage to damage your characters it's because of something which would seem more like a game bug then legitimate gameplay;
- Leveling up is weird, it's like you're getting XP for discovering monsters, not killing them. And when you character reaches final level, you can reset his feats and start training in other class.

Other then that, game is fine, crushing walls in robot suit is fun :)
